@node Introduction "CleanDisk Documentation - Introduction"

The idea of this program is simple. Whenever data on an AmigaDOS drive is deleted,
only the references are removed by the filesystem, the data still remains
on the media.

This can be annoying when playing around with copy protection algorithms or
when working with secret data that must be stored in uncrypted form on a
disk temporarily. Every advanced user could restore the deleted valuable
information easily.

The idea of this program is based on Fred Fish's @{b}'FillDisk'@{ub} which
was using buffered IO and therefore was slow. @{b}CleanDisk@{ub} is
faster and is very 3.0-ish. It allocates a rather large IO buffer (currently
64 kB) in 24BITDMA-memory and therefore has a good performance. It writes
out the 64 kB buffer which is filled with Null's in a loop and does this
until the disk is full.

After filling the disk successfully, @{b}CleanDisk@{ub} removes its file
from the drive.

This technique has a minor disadvantage: on @{u}XPK-packed devices@{uu}, writing
a file consisting of zeros is nonsense. Writing directly to the host drive
is the better sollution.

Another minor problem has been reported in conjunction with @{u}AFS partitions@{uu}.
When @{b}CleanDisk@{ub}'ing them, the @{i}.deldir@{ui} which (should) hold all
recoverable deleted files doesn't get cleared. Instead, the old entries
remain in the directory, but the associated data is being deleted.

For cleaning up your system memory, you should not @{b}CleanDisk@{ub} your @{u}RAM-Drive@{uu},
even though it works. There are more sophisticated and efficient methods for
doing this.

Created using SAS/C 6.56.

@endnode


@node Usage "CleanDisk Documentation - Usage"

@{b}CleanDisk@{ub} can be used from Shell only.

1> CleanDisk DIR/A

@{i}Example:@{ui} CleanDisk hd1:

@{b}DIR@{ub} is the name of the drive or directory to write the data to.
@{b}CleanDisk@{ub} will open a file with a unique name in the form
'tmp.xxxxxxxx' and will then start writing to the directory until the disk
is full. After that, it will remove the file and display how many bytes
were written.

@endnode


